entry.summary:
This blog, I will post my proof about the expectation of absolute distance in Random walk is ${\Theta(\sqrt{i})}$ at ${i}$th step. Statement of Problem Consider a sequence of $n$ flips of an unbiased coin. Let $H_i$ denote the absolute value of the excess of then number of HEADS over the number of TAILS seen in the first $i$ flips. Show that $E[H_i] = \Theta(\sqrt{i})$. We can also treat is as a 1D random walk problem. Idea of my proof Use the relation between Expectation and Variance to get the upper bound $\sqrt{i}$. Solve the recursive formula of $E[H_i]$, which can give us a sense of growth speed. We can prove the lower bound greater than ${C\sqrt{i}}$ by induction, where C ranges from $0$ to $1$. Lemma 1: $\mathbb{E}[H_i]$ satisfies following recursive formula \[ egin{equation} \mathbb{E}[H_i] =  egin{cases} \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] +  rac{1}{2^{i-1}}  inom{i-1}{(i-1)/2}, &amp; n 	ext{ is odd,}\ \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}],&amp; n 	ext{ is even.} \end{cases}
onumber \end{equation}\] Proof. By definition, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_i] &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert \Pr[k 	ext{ HEADS in first } i 	ext{ flips}] \ &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] If $i$ is even and $i-1$ is odd. We have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_i] &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} \ &amp; = \vert -i + 2(i/2) \vert  inom{i}{i/2}  rac{1}{2^i} + 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2+1}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} (-i + 2k)  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} + 2 \vert -i + 2i \vert  inom{i}{i}  rac{1}{2^i} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} (-i + 2k)  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] And \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i-1} \vert -i+1 + 2k \vert  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 2\cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} \vert -i+1 + 2k \vert  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} ( -i+1 + 2k )  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}}\ \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] Then, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_i] - \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] &amp;= 2 \cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} (-i + 2k)  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} - 2\cdot \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} ( -i+1 + 2k )  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 2\left(\sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1} (-i + 2k)  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^i} - ( -i+1 + 2k )  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\left(\sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1}  rac{(-i + 2k)}{2^i} \left(  inom{i-1}{k} +  inom{i-1}{k-1}ight)-  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{( -i+1 + 2k )}{2^{i-1}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\left(\sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1}  rac{(-i + 2k)}{2^i}  inom{i-1}{k-1} +  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{( i -2 - 2k )}{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\left(\sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1}  rac{(-i + 2k)}{2^i}  inom{i-1}{k-1} - \sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1}  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{( -i +2 + 2k )}{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\left(\sum_{k=i/2}^{i-1}  rac{(-i + 2k)}{2^i}  inom{i-1}{k-1} - \sum_{j=i/2+1}^{i}  inom{i-1}{j-1}  rac{( -i + 2j )}{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2\left(  rac{(-i + 2(i/2))}{2^i}  inom{i-1}{i/2-1} -  inom{i-1}{i-1}  rac{( -i + 2i )}{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 2\left( 0\cdot  inom{i-1}{i/2-1} -  inom{i-1}{i-1}  rac{i}{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 0 \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] If $i$ is odd and $i-1$ is even. We have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_{i}] &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} \ &amp; = \sum_{k=0}^{(i-1)/2} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} + \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} \ &amp; = 2\cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i} \vert -i + 2k \vert  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}}\ &amp; = 2\cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} ( -i + 2k )  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} + 2 \cdot ( -i + 2i )  inom{i}{i}  rac{1}{2^{i}} \ &amp; = 2\cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} ( -i + 2k )  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} \ \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] And \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] &amp;= \sum_{k=0}^{i-1} \vert -i+1 + 2k \vert  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} (-i+1 + 2k)  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] Then, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_i] - \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] &amp;= 2\cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} ( -i + 2k )  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}} - 2 \cdot \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} (-i+1 + 2k)  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} \ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(\sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1} ( -i + 2k )  inom{i}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i}} - (-i+1 + 2k)  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{1}{2^{i-1}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(\sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1}  rac{( -i + 2k )}{2^{i}} \left( inom{i-1}{k} +  inom{i-1}{k-1}ight) - inom{i-1}{k}  rac{ (-i+1 + 2k) }{2^{i-1}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(\sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1}  rac{( -i + 2k )}{2^{i}}  inom{i-1}{k-1}+ inom{i-1}{k}  rac{ (i-2 - 2k) }{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(\sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1}  rac{( -i + 2k )}{2^{i}}  inom{i-1}{k-1} - \sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1}  inom{i-1}{k}  rac{ (-i+2 + 2k) }{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(\sum_{k=(i+1)/2}^{i-1}  rac{( -i + 2k )}{2^{i}}  inom{i-1}{k-1} - \sum_{j=(i+3)/2}^{i}  inom{i-1}{j-1}  rac{ (-i+2 j) }{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; = 2 \cdot \left(  rac{( -i + 2((i+1)/2) )}{2^{i}}  inom{i-1}{(i+1)/2-1} -  inom{i-1}{i-1}  rac{ (-i+2 i) }{2^{i}} ight) +  rac{i}{2^{i-1}}\ &amp; =  rac{1}{2^{i-1}}  inom{i-1}{(i-1)/2} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] Hence, we prove the recursive formula \[ egin{equation} \mathbb{E}[H_i] =  egin{cases} \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}] +  rac{1}{2^{i-1}}  inom{i-1}{(i-1)/2}, &amp; n 	ext{ is odd,}\ \mathbb{E}[H_{i-1}],&amp; n 	ext{ is even.} \end{cases}
onumber \quad \quad \quad \square \end{equation}\] Theorem 1: $\mathbb{E}[H_i] = \Theta(\sqrt{i})$. Proof. First, Let’s show $\mathbb{E}[H_i] \leq \sqrt{i}$ Denote the random variable $X_j, j=1,2,\cdots, i$ as below \[ egin{equation} X_j= egin{cases} 1 &amp; 	ext{HEAD is seen in } i 	ext{th flip}\ -1 &amp; 	ext{TAIL is seen in } i 	ext{th flip}\ \end{cases}
onumber \end{equation}\] It’s easy to have $H_i = \vert \sum_{j=1}^i X_i \vert $, $\mathbb{E}[X_i]=0$ and we know $X_1,X_2,\cdots,X_i$ are pairwise independent. By the definition of variance $\mathbb{D}[H_i]$, we have $\mathbb{D}[H_i] = \mathbb{E}[H_i^2] - (\mathbb{E}[H_i])^2$. Then we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} (\mathbb{E}[H_i])^2 = \mathbb{E}[H_i^2] - \mathbb{D}[H_i] \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] Because $X_1,X_2,\cdots,X_i$ are pairwise independent, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_i^2] &amp; = \mathbb{E}\left[\left(\sum_{j=1}^i X_jight)^2ight] \ &amp; = \sum_{j=1}^i \mathbb{E}[X_j^2] + 2 \sum_{j&lt;k} \mathbb{E}[X_j X_k]\ &amp; = \sum_{j=1}^i \mathbb{E}[X_j^2] + 2 \sum_{j&lt;k} \mathbb{E}[X_j] \mathbb{E}[X_k]\ &amp; = i \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] $(\mathbb{E}[H_i])^2 = \mathbb{E}[H_i^2] - \mathbb{D}[H_i]$ that means $(\mathbb{E}[H_i])^2 \leq \mathbb{E}[H_i^2] = i$. Thus $\mathbb{E}[H_i] \leq \sqrt{i}$. We will show $\mathbb{E}[H_i] &gt; C \sqrt{i}, C=e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}$ by induction (It’s clear $0&lt;C&lt;1$) Base case: For $i=1$, we know $\mathbb{E}[H_1] = \vert 1 \vert \cdot  rac{1}{2}+\vert -1 \vert \cdot  rac{1}{2} = 1 &gt; C \sqrt{1}$. And for $i=2$, we know $\mathbb{E}[H_2] = \vert 2 \vert \cdot  rac{1}{4} +\vert -2 \vert \cdot  rac{1}{4} + 0 \cdot  rac{1}{2} = 1 &gt;  rac{\sqrt{2}}{e} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}} = C \sqrt{2} $.\ Induction Hypothesis: $\mathbb{E}[H_j] &gt;  rac{\sqrt{j}}{2},  orall j \leq k$ We will show ${\mathbb{E}[H_{k+1}] &gt;  rac{\sqrt{k+1}}{2}}$ in the following If $k+1$ is even: By Lemma 1, $\mathbb{E}[H_{k+1}] = \mathbb{E}[H_{k}] = \mathbb{E}[H_{k-1}] +  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  inom{k-1}{(k-1)/2} $. Then, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned}  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  inom{k-1}{(k-1)/2} &amp; =  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  rac{(k-1)!}{\left(\left( rac{k-1}{2}ight)!ight)^2} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] By Stirling formula, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned}  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  inom{k-1}{(k-1)/2} &amp; =  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  rac{(k-1)!}{\left(\left( rac{k-1}{2}ight)!ight)^2} \ &amp; &gt;  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  rac{\sqrt{2 \pi (k-1)} \left( rac{k-1}{e}ight)^{k-1}}{\pi (k-1) \left( rac{k-1}{2e}ight)^{k-1} e^ rac{1}{12(k-1)}}\ &amp; = e^{- rac{1}{12(k-1)}} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}  rac{1}{\sqrt{k-1}}\ &amp; &gt; e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}  rac{1}{\sqrt{k-1}}\ &amp; = e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}  rac{2}{2\sqrt{k-1}}&gt; C  rac{2}{\sqrt{k+1} + \sqrt{k-1}} = C (\sqrt{k+1} - \sqrt{k-1}) \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] By induction hypothesis, $\mathbb{E}[H_{k-1}] &gt; C\sqrt{k-1}$, that means \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_{k+1}] &amp;= \mathbb{E}[H_{k}] \ &amp;= \mathbb{E}[H_{k-1}] +  rac{1}{2^{k-1}}  inom{k-1}{(k-1)/2}\ &amp; &gt; C\sqrt{k-1} + C (\sqrt{k+1} - \sqrt{k-1}) \ &amp; = C \sqrt{k+1} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] If $k+1$ is odd: By Lemma 1, $\mathbb{E}[H_{k+1}] = \mathbb{E}[H_{k}] +  rac{1}{2^{k}}  inom{k}{k/2} $. Then, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned}  rac{1}{2^{k}}  inom{k}{k/2} &amp; =  rac{1}{2^{k}}  rac{k!}{\left(\left( rac{k}{2}ight)!ight)^2} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] By Stirling formula, we have \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned}  rac{1}{2^{k}}  inom{k}{k/2} &amp; &gt;  rac{1}{2^{k}}  rac{\sqrt{2 \pi k} \left( rac{k}{e}ight)^{k}}{\pi k \left( rac{k}{2e}ight)^{k} e^ rac{1}{12k}}\ &amp; &gt; e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}  rac{1}{\sqrt{k}}\ &amp; &gt; e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}  rac{1}{2\sqrt{k}}&gt; C  rac{1}{\sqrt{k+1} + \sqrt{k}} = C (\sqrt{k+1} - \sqrt{k}) \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] By induction hypothesis, $\mathbb{E}[H_{k}] &gt; C\sqrt{k}$, that means \[ egin{equation}  egin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[H_{k+1}] &amp;= \mathbb{E}[H_{k}] +  rac{1}{2^{k}}  inom{k}{k/2}\ &amp; &gt; C\sqrt{k} + C (\sqrt{k+1} - \sqrt{k}) \ &amp; = C \sqrt{k+1} \end{aligned}
onumber \end{equation}\] Hence, we show $\mathbb{E}[H_i] &gt; C \sqrt{i}, C=e^{-1} \sqrt{ rac{2}{\pi}}$, and $\mathbb{E}[H_i] \leq \sqrt{i}$, which imply $\mathbb{E}[H_i] = \Theta(\sqrt{i})$. $\square$
